[1]
Date: Mon 22 May 2006
From: Joe Dudley <jdudley@eaicorp.com>
Source: Bucharest Daily News, 22 May 2006 [edited]
<http://www.daily-news.ro/article_detail.php?idarticle=26531>

Bird flu triggers temporary quarantine in capital's neighborhood
-----------------------------------------------
After a series of preliminary tests revealed on Friday [19 May 2006] that
some domestic poultry in Bucharest might be carrying the H5 bird flu virus,
prompting authorities to quarantine a street in the Andronache neighborhood
of Sector 4 and restrict access to other areas in Sector 2, President
Traian Basescu got involved in managing the bird flu crisis and requested
the head of the Intelligence Services, Radu Timofte, to collect information
about an alleged illegal import of chickens that, according to Agriculture
Minister Gheorghe Flutur, might have led to the spread of the disease.
Although still in hospital, Basescu had a meeting with Timofte and urged
him to find out whether Flutur's suspicions are true, pointing out that the
rapid spread of the virus represents an issue of national security. On
Saturday [20 May 2006], the president also had a meeting with Prime
Minister Calin Popescu Tariceanu, Flutur, and Interior Minister Vasile
Blaga, calling on them to check all the poultry farms in the areas where
the virus hasn't yet been reported.
"The president asked the ministers to take immediate measures to prevent
the spreading of the disease and demanded disinfecting filters be
established in the counties neighboring those areas affected by the bird
flu," presidential aide Adriana Saftoiu said on Saturday [20 May 2006].
The bird flu outbreak in Bucharest created panic, despite the officials'
appeal for calm. "The virus has been confirmed in the 2nd district" of
Bucharest, where there are more than 400 households that have some 4400
chickens, Mayor Adriean Videanu said, adding that further tests will
determine whether the dead poultry had the deadly H5N1 strain of bird flu
virus.
The final tests confirmed the virus yesterday [21 May 2006], and the
authorities enforced the Level 1 quarantine measures, which are meant to
isolate a 3rd of the households in sectors 2 and 4. Authorities quarantined
at least one street in an eastern part of the capital on Saturday [20 May
2006] and began culling birds and disinfecting streets in the 2 districts.
Access was restricted to 65 streets in both districts, where about 2000
residents live, Videanu said. Meanwhile, the residents were given the
antiviral drug Tamiflu.
Bucharest's chief veterinarian, Constantin Savu, said that authorities are
considering ordering a ban on poultry husbandry in the city. An estimated
40 000 domestic birds could be culled.
However, after yesterday's [21 May 2006] meeting of the National Emergency
Department for the Fight Against Bird Flu, Flutur urged calm, stressing
that the situation is being stabilized. According to Flutur, yesterday
there were 25 confirmed outbreaks of H5N1 bird flu in 6 counties, with
Brasov County leading with 16 affected localities.
"In 15 of these localities, the sanitary-veterinary experts have already
finished culling the birds and have disinfected the areas. By tonight, all
25 locations will be disinfected," said Flutur, adding that 26 other areas
are suspected of hosting the H5 virus. The minister also said the
authorities have finished culling the birds at the Dakrom poultry farm in
Codlea, which is considered to be the source of the bird flu outbreak.
"Today, we have started to cull the birds at Pati Prod (another farm in
Codlea). The experts have to incinerate about 600 000 chickens," Flutur
explained.
Meanwhile, prosecutors in Brasov County issued a temporary custody warrant
for the manager of Pati Prod, Florin Macovei. Macovei will be detained for
20 days, the same as the owner of Dakrom, Vasile Dardala, who was taken
into custody at the end of last week. The 2 businessmen are being
investigated for tax evasion and spreading of animal disease, as they sold
chickens to several supermarkets in the country despite the fact they did
not have authorization to do so.
Meanwhile, more and more people in Bucharest have reported dead birds, but
the preliminary tests did not confirm the H5 virus. In addition, none of
the 14 people brought last week to the Matei Bals Institute for Infectious
Disease were found to carry the virus, according to the Institute's
director, Doctor Adrian Streinu Cercel. "Numerous persons came to us in the
last weekend, afraid they might be infected with bird flu. They were not
sick, but the panic creates fear. In fact, they have reasons to be worried,
because the virus spreads through air," pointed out Streinu Cercel.
[Byline: Denisa Maruntoiu]
--
