[3]
Date: Mon 22 May 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Nine-o'clock, Bucharest, issue 3683, 22 May 2006 [edited]
<http://www.nineoclock.ro/index.php?page=detalii&categorie=frontpage&id=20060522-500671>

There are so many controversies surrounding the re-outburst of avian flu
that it defies explanation and, therefore, its management within the
sanitary limits available. Within the space of only a few days, scores of
foci, confirmed or only supposed, emerged across 1/3rd of the surface area
of this country, the threat of spreading including Romania's capital
itself, hence, the frequent questions about this phenomenon almost unique
in contemporary Europe. Why was it -- both the experts and the public ask
-- that once the serious foci of avian influenza were fast and definitively
closed last March 2005 (the reason for which Romania received praise from
the EU), they burst out again and in several locations concurrently? And
why is it that in those locations, the migratory birds, unanimously
acknowledged to be the carriers of the deadly virus, have not showed signs
of sickness this time around?
What favored the pathogenic agent in such places as Brasov, Fagaras, Codlea
etc., where, unlike the Danube Meadow or Delta, the environment is not
propitious for such disease? And why have prevention measures not been
enforced in all the aforementioned localities, and why have veterinary
doctors, who are 1st responsible for the health of all domestic animals and
birds, actually been the 1st to break the law?
The questions don't stop here. They are equally rooted in the fact that,
although banned after the recent avian flu crisis, the sales and, likely,
the import of live chickens carried on out of control. In the commune of
Balotesti, Vrancea County, but in other locations as well, even the local
authorities opposed the quarantine measures. Even the National Veterinary
Sanitary Administration continues to operate as an entity autonomous from
the chief coordinating factor, the Ministry of Agriculture. And since here
"autonomy" means "opposition" most often than not, it is quite clear that
such top-down measures for preventing, and consequently fighting, avian
influenza have turned into the opposite, a fact proven by none other than
the Agriculture minister himself, who, in a recent appeal to local
authorities, insisted, in comical-tragic fashion, on specifying that,
"during the crisis, the Command must stay in Bucharest."
[Byline: Mihai Iordanescu]
--
