[4]
Date: Mon 22 May 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Nine-o'clock, Bucharest, 22 May 2006 [edited]
<http://www.nineoclock.ro/index.php?page=detalii&categorie=homenews&id=20060521-5154>

The H5N1 strain was confirmed late on Sunday [21 May 2006] by the Weybridge
Laboratory in U.K. in the samples from Brasov County. No other information
has become available since the newspaper went to print.
25 foci have been confirmed now in 6 counties: 16 in Brasov county, one in
Covasna county, 3 in Vrancea county, 3 in Bacau county, one in Buzau
county, one in Sibiu county (in the city of Sibiu).
The number of suspected cases has decreased from 31 to 26 -- due to 5
suspected cases becoming confirmed cases -- in Bacau, Buzau and Sibiu
Counties. On Sunday [21 May 2006] morning, there were 26 suspected cases:
11 in Brasov, 2 in Buzau, 2 in Vrancea, 4 in Valcea, one in Sibiu, 2 in
Prahova, one in Alba, one in Neamt, and 2 in Bucharest [see
political/administrative map of Romania at
<http://www.aboutromania.com/maps3.html>].
Minister Gheorghe Flutur stressed that 15 foci have been already cleared,
all the chickens having been culled, making the 1st disinfection. The
liquidated foci are in Brasov (11 total: 10 in localities and one at Drakom
farm), Covasna (1), Buzau (1), Sibiu (1). The other hotbeds where the
presence of the virus H5 was confirmed will be liquidated by Monday [22 May
2006] evening, except for the focus in Patiprod, where the action will take
several days. Nevertheless, the culling is taking place with great
difficulty. The culling has not begun at chicken farm No. 3 of Patiprod, at
Codlea, where there are 600 000 chickens. Culling was not started at
chicken farm No. 4 from the same complex, where the tests were negative.
The manager of the farm complains that the birds have started to die,
because they haven't been fed for a week, and corpses lie on the farm
floor. In response, the Codlea mayor said that equipment and teams sent to
the culling sites are insufficient.
The meeting of the Central Anti-epizootic task force on Sunday [21 May
2006] was attended also by Premier Calin Popescu Tariceanu, who wanted to
discuss with its members the handling of bird flu. The Prime Minister also
informed the members about the involvement of the other ministries in the
management of the crisis and consulted the specialists over certain
technical details. "I think that the Premier left the place optimistic,
because he saw that the situation begins to calm down, and the authorities
are doing their duty," concluded Minister Gheorghe Flutur.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The situation in Romania is a reminder of the long-known fact that HPAI
spreads by 2 main routes: on the one hand by free-roaming birds; but
certainly not less important, by uncontrolled trade and transportation of
infected domestic or captive birds, poultry products, fomites, people,
vehicles etc. Biosecurity measures should address all of them.
The 1st case of HPAI H5N1 was detected in Romania in October 2005 in ducks
within the Danube delta, Europe's largest wetland. An interactive map of
avian influenza monitoring in Europe and the Middle East, showing recorded
cases in domestic fowl, wild birds, mammals and humans, is available at
<http://disasters.jrc.it/AvianFlu/Europe/>.
On top of the apprehension caused by the well-known potential human-health
implications of H5N1, the public and media response observed in Bucharest
might have been exacerbated by imprinted fears caused by another zoonosis,
West Nile fever, which affected Romania's capital in 1996, causing several
hundred cases and at least 17 mortalities.
The world HPAI situation will be one of the topics to be discussed during
this week's 74th General annual session of the OIE in Paris (21 - 26 May
2006), where the 165 member countries will be represented by their
respective Chief Veterinary Officers. International organizations and
animal-health experts will participate as well. Romania's official delegate
to the OIE is Dr. Gabriel Predoi. - Mod.AS]
